# Tricks/PairPeel.elm — WORKHORSE

PAIR_PEEL: two hand cards form a pair (set-pair or run-pair)
and a peelable board card completes the triplet into a valid
3-stack.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE. Stable.
- **Go counterpart ripped 2026-04-20** (`project_hints_are_client_side.md`).

## The three pair shapes + their "needs"

Given two distinct hand cards `a, b`:

1. **Set pair** — same value, different suits. Needs: same
   value, in any of the TWO remaining suits (both are
   candidates).
2. **Pure-run pair** — same suit, consecutive values. Needs:
   `predecessor(lo)` OR `successor(hi)`, both in the same
   suit. Up to two needs emitted.
3. **Rb-run pair** — consecutive values, DIFFERENT colors.
   Needs: `predecessor(lo)` in either opposite-color suit of
   `lo`, OR `successor(hi)` in either opposite-color suit of
   `hi`. Up to four candidate (value, suit) combinations.

Any other pair shape: empty needs list → trick emits nothing
for that pair.

## Equality filter on hand pairs

`handPairs` skips pairs where `cardsEqual a.card b.card` —
same value + suit + originDeck. Double-deck dups can't pair
with themselves.

## Scan: extractable candidates only

`scanBoardForNeed` filters with `canExtract` — only cards
that can legally be peeled (see `CardStack.canExtract`) count.
Cards sealed inside 3-card runs are invisible here.

## Apply-time safety

`applyPairPeel`:
1. Re-reads the target card at `(si, ci)`; refuses if it
   moved or isn't `canExtract`.
2. Calls `extractCard` to peel.
3. Sorts `[hca, hcb, extracted]` by card value, builds a new
   stack at `dummyLoc`.
4. Classifies the result; if `Bogus`, `Dup`, or `Incomplete`,
   refuses.
5. Otherwise, appends the new stack and returns the
   consumed hand cards.

The classification check in step 4 is belt-and-suspenders —
`pairNeeds` should only emit valid combinations, but
re-checking at apply time catches any drift.

## Key exports

- `trick : Trick` — `id = "pair_peel"`, description: "Peel a
  board card to complete a pair in your hand."

## Pointers

- Python counterpart: `hints.pair_peel` in
  `tools/lynrummy_elm_player/hints.py` (emits primitives).
  Python had ordering bugs on this trick; Elm does not — see
  `tricks.dsl` `hint_invariant_pair_peel_run_pair_reversed_hand`.
- Depends on: `Card`, `CardStack.canExtract`, `StackType`
  (`successor`/`predecessor`/`getStackType`),
  `Tricks.Helpers.extractCard`.
- Consumer: `Tricks.Hint.allTricks`.
